<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>child’s game • child’s play</xh5><p> <i>child’s game—</i>said of a person’s behavior more appropriate for a child: He knew it was just a <u>child’s game</u>—to stare at someone and not look away first.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>easy game</b>—(also: fair game) a suitable object for ridicule; a person easily persuaded or taken advantage of: So I disguised myself and came back and studied you. You were <u>easy game</u>.</p><p> <i>child’s play—</i>said of smth. very easily done or of very little importance: The work of reformation is <u>child’s play</u> to that of making your friends believe you have reformed.</p> </entry>
